09154nam a22010455i 9781531503000DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815315030007 a10.1515/97815315030002doi  a(DE-B1597)644872  a(OCoLC)1391383609  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aREL1020002bisacsh04a200.899622300aLife Under the Baobab Tree :bAfricana Studies and Religion in a Transitional Age /ced. by Kenneth N. Ngwa, Aliou Cissé Niang, Arthur Pressley. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (416 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTransdisciplinary Theological Colloquia00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction. Life Under the Baobab Tree: Africana Studies and Religion in a Transitional Age -- tPART I -- tUN/FOLDING IDENTITIES -- t1. Nella Larsen’s Quicksand: Mourning through Biracial Identities -- t2. Body as Praxis: Disarticulating the Human from Ownership and Property -- t3. What It’s Like to Be a Blackened Body, and Why It’s Like That: A Preliminary Exploration -- t4. The Rhizome and/as the Tree of Life: The Relational Poetics of Wisdom and Decolonizing Biblical Studies -- t5. Senghorian Négritude and Postcolonial Biblical Criticism -- tPART II -- tAFRICANA ACTIVISM -- t6. God Killed! God Interrupted, Long Live the People!: Political Theory in Religious Act -- t7. “Doing the Will of God” as Loving God Whose Way Is Peace -- t8. Mysticism and Mothering in Black Women’s Social Justice Activism: Brazil/USA -- t9. A Theopoetics of Exodus and the Africana Spirit in Music -- t10. Must We Burn Isaac?: A Four-Part Hermeneutical Fantasy for Africana Epistemology -- tPART III -- tAFRICANA HISTORIOGRAPHIES AND MEMORIES -- t11. From White Man’s Magic to Black Folks’ Wisdom -- t12. Solidarity by Sharing Power: An Inculturated Organic Storytelling of Jonah and Mami Wata -- t13. Envisioning Africana Religions: Seeking a Distinctive Voice for the Study of Religions in Africa and the African Diaspora -- t14. Interpreting from the Back/Black-Side: Exodus through the Shawl of Memory -- t15. Conjuring Lost Books: (Re-)membering Fragmented Litanies at the Intersection of Africana and Biblical Studies -- tAfterword -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex of Modern Authors -- tIndex of Ancient Documents0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLife Under the Baobab Tree: Africana Studies and Religion in a Transitional Age is a compendium of innovating essays meticulously written by early and later diaspora people of African descent. Their speech arises from the depth of their experiences under the Baobab Tree and offers to the world voices of resilience, newness/resurrection, hope, and life. Resolutely journeying on the trails of their ancestors, they speak about setbacks and forward-looking movements of liberation, social transformation, and community formation. The volume is a carefully woven conversation of intellectual substance and structure across time, space, and spirituality that is quintessentially “Africana” in its centering of methodological, theoretical, epistemological, and hermeneutical complexity that assumes non-linear and dialogical approaches to developing liberating epistemologies in the face of imperialism, colonialism, racism, and religious intolerance. A critical part of this conversation is a reconceptualization and reconfiguration of the concept of religion in its colonial and imperial forms. Life Under the Baobab Tree examines how Africana peoples understand their corporate experiences of the divine not as “religion” apart from its intimate connections to social realities of communal health, economics, culture, politics, environment, violence, war, and dynamic community belonging. To that end Afro-Pessimistic formulations of life placed in dialogic relation Afro-Optimism. Both realities constitute life under the Baobab tree, and represent the sturdiness and variation that anchors the deep ruptures that have impacted Africana life, and the creative responses. The metaphor and substance of the Tree resists reductionist, essentialist, and assured conclusions about the nature of diasporic lived experiences, both within the continent of Africa and in the African Diaspora.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBlack peoplexReligion. 0aBlack peoplexStudy and teaching. 0aBlack theology. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aReligion. 4aTheology. 7aRELIGION / Theology.2bisacsh  aAfricana Biblical Studies.  aAfricana.  aDiaspora Spirituality.  aMemory.  aNegritude.  aOrality.  aPoetics of Spirituality.  aStorytelling.  aWomanist Political Activism.1 aAdegbite, Shola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAdegbite, ’Shola D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColeman, Desmond D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColeman, Desmond, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaraji, Salim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarding, Rachel E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarding, Rachel Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeller, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhumalo, Minenhle Nomalungelo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Althea Spencer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMordecai, Pamela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNgwa, Kenneth N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNg